CC0 1.0 Universal — Public Domain Dedication
===========================================

The label data in this directory (high_risk.json, mixers.json,
ransomware.json, defi_protocols.json, cex_deposits.json,
issuers.json, bridges.json, and any future *.json files) is
released under Creative Commons CC0 1.0 — public domain, no
rights reserved.

You may copy, modify, distribute, and use the data, even for
commercial purposes, without asking permission. Attribution is
appreciated but not required.

Why public domain
-----------------

TRM Labs and Chainalysis treat their address-label databases as
proprietary trade secrets. The result is that every forensic
investigator, every recovery firm, every state AG's office, every
class-action attorney pays for access to the same fundamental
facts: "0x47CE0C6... is Tornado Cash 0.1 ETH."

Those facts are not creative works. They're observations of
public-blockchain reality. Recupero releases its curated label
data into the public domain so:

  - Other recovery operators, even competitors, can use it.
  - Independent researchers can build on it.
  - Victims of crypto theft don't need a $100k/year enterprise
    license to identify the addresses that took their money.
  - The community can contribute new labels back, raising the
    quality floor for everyone.

CC0 1.0 Universal full text: https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/

The CODE that consumes this data (everything outside this
seeds/ directory) is licensed separately per the repo root's
LICENSE. Public-domain release applies ONLY to the .json data
files in this directory.
